2.1: Create an Android app that defines custom colors in colors.xml and applies them to the background of a TextView 

STEP 1 — Create New Project 
1. Open Android Studio 
2. Click New Project 
3. Select Empty Views Activity 
4. Click Next 
5. Fill details: 
      Project Name: Practical2_1_CustomColors 
      Package Name: (auto) 
      Language: Java 
      Minimum SDK: API 21 
6. Click Finish 
Android separates reusable items into folders under res/ 
Examples: 
      • colors.xml → stores color definitions 
      • strings.xml → stores text 
      • styles.xml → themes 
      • layout.xml → UI structure 
This practical focuses on colors.xml 

STEP 3 — Define Custom Colors in colors.xml 
    Go to: 
    app → res → values → colors.xml 
    Replace everything inside with: 
    <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?> 
    <resources> 
    <color name="myBackground">#FF9800</color>   <!-- Orange --> 
    <color name="myTextColor">#FFFFFF</color>    <!-- White --> 
    </resources> 

STEP 4 — Design the UI in activity_main.xml 
Go to 
app → res → layout → activity_main.xml 
Replace with: 
        <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?> 
        <LinearLayout 
        xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android" 
        android:orientation="vertical" 
        android:layout_width="match_parent" 
        android:layout_height="match_parent" 
        android:gravity="center"> 
        <TextView 
        android:id="@+id/txtSample" 
        android:layout_width="wrap_content" 
        android:layout_height="wrap_content" 
        android:text="Hello Custom Colors!" 
        android:textSize="24sp" 
        android:padding="20dp" /> 
        </LinearLayout> 
Why not set colors here? 
Because practical requires setting color using Java code. 

STEP 5 — Write Java code in MainActivity.java 
Go to: 
app → java → yourpackagename → MainActivity.java 
Replace code with: 
        package com.example.practical2_1_customcolors; 
        import android.os.Bundle; 
        import android.widget.TextView; 
        import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity; 
        public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity { 
        @Override 
        protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) { 
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState); 
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main); 
        // Step 1: Find TextView by ID 
        TextView txt = findViewById(R.id.txtSample); 
        // Step 2: Apply custom colors from colors.xml 
        txt.setBackgroundColor(getResources().getColor(R.color.myBackground)); 
        txt.setTextColor(getResources().getColor(R.color.myTextColor)); 
        } 
        } 
STEP 6 — Run the App 
1. Choose Emulator or Physical Device 
2. Press Run ▶ 
3. Output Expected: 
A screen displaying: 
Orange background TextView 
White text inside 
Text: Hello Custom Colors!
